        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer581463550" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8990546340743207735">Review copy kindly provided by author and Goodreads friend Paul Haston.<br/><br/>This novel narrates the story of Usha, a Bengali girl who is forced into an arranged marriage and shunned by her own family as well as her husband&apos;s when she becomes a widow. In an effort to locate her father who has disappeared, she goes to South Africa and ends up in even more dire straits. A chance meeting with Lt. James Rothwell, an Englishman lacking the usual imperialist prejudices, gives her a glimpse of hope, but she </span>
  <span id="freeText8990546340743207735" style="display:none">Review copy kindly provided by author and Goodreads friend Paul Haston.<br /><br />This novel narrates the story of Usha, a Bengali girl who is forced into an arranged marriage and shunned by her own family as well as her husband's when she becomes a widow. In an effort to locate her father who has disappeared, she goes to South Africa and ends up in even more dire straits. A chance meeting with Lt. James Rothwell, an Englishman lacking the usual imperialist prejudices, gives her a glimpse of hope, but she goes through many trials before she meets him again.<br /><br />Haston does a very good job conveying the mindset of a young Indian woman. Her attitude to religion, gender roles, and the colonial system brings her plight and that of her people into extremely sharp focus. Although I thought Rothwell was a perhaps a little too forward-thinking for his time and place, there are examples of such people in history. And his relative open-mindedness and purity of feeling serves to underline the racism, indifference and corruption of the British colonials who maintain a system practically identical with slavery. <br /><br />The story is told with great intensity. The plot is full of twists and turns which keep the reader engaged, but the ending was a surprise. I did find that there were some problems with syntax and punctuation; however these were not great enough to lessen the force of the message. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8990546340743207735" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


