  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_649637271" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/649637271" />
    <a title="Lynelle Clark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8713879-lynelle-clark"><img alt="Lynelle Clark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598989985p2/8713879.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/649637271?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynelle Clark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynelle Clark" href="/user/show/8713879-lynelle-clark">Lynelle Clark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=arc-receive">arc-receive</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=romance">romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=war">war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=forbidden-love">forbidden-love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8713879-lynelle-clark?shelf=history-of-south-africa">history-of-south-africa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer649637271" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2506602444688738517">I received this book from the author for an honest review.<br/><br/>I really did like this book. Filled with intrigue, the rich history of Natal, South Africa and the Indian culture you are taken back in the colonial time when the English was still in control of the land. The arrogance of them coming here, ruling and making their own laws that only suite them was evident throughout. And even after Independence and democracy the legacy that the English left still causes many problems we still have to face </span>
  <span id="freeText2506602444688738517" style="display:none">I received this book from the author for an honest review.<br /><br />I really did like this book. Filled with intrigue, the rich history of Natal, South Africa and the Indian culture you are taken back in the colonial time when the English was still in control of the land. The arrogance of them coming here, ruling and making their own laws that only suite them was evident throughout. And even after Independence and democracy the legacy that the English left still causes many problems we still have to face as a nation. <br />None of us is better then the next person. It does not matter the color of the skin, we have the same blood that flows through our veins, the same needs. The author did a splendid job creating this story with the backdrop of the defeat at Isandlwana, the victories over the Zulu empire and the general life in Durban, capital of Natal.<br /><br />It is a story about a young Indian woman, Usha who came to SA on a quest to search for her father who left for SA when she was 6. Believing the lies of the man in India she signed up for the indenture and ended up working on the cane fields of Natal in the most horrific conditions. The unforgiving heat of the country, the constant abuse and living conditions, gave this woman pause to think about her life and her unrelenting belief in her religion that sustained her throughout the plot line. Abused by her In-laws and rejected by a mother she thought it best to go away. On her first day, she met a young officer who became her radiant light and savior in so many ways.<br />A wonderful young woman, strong in character, strong in the body and a faith to keep her going was endearing and wonderfully created to make this a remarkable read. <br /><br />Lt. James Rothwell was a young officer in the British army, and when he nearly lost his life on the battlefield returned to England where guilt and the sense of duty helped him to make a huge mistake that cost him nearly everything dear to his heart. Battling with dreams and a crippled leg he returned back to Natal after inheriting a cane plantation. Finding the conditions horrific he went about to change the standard practices of his people. This caused many problems throughout the story. With a magistrate that has no problem taking bribes to line his own pockets. The bank that did not accept his relationship and a wife that was not willing to see and love the country as he did. His character is believable, likable, and I had the greatest respect for him as he went about to change the attitude of his own people towards the coolies. Trying to save the one woman who had his heart in her hands.<br /><br />Annabelle's character, a typical English lady, hypocritical, prejudice and selfish in her ways caused many problems in their marriage and at the end she flee back to England creating lies that would cost Usha dearly.<br /><br />Royston was a real piece of work, an abusive, filthy, drunk skunk that tried to weazzle more money out from the new land owner. Not caring about anyone but himself. His attitude offensive and really living the villain well.<br /><br />It is a tale of forbidden love in a time when coolies were not seen as people. Of a father daughter relationship that needs restoration. Overcoming all the odds to find peace and happiness.<br /><br />And the end...it will leave you speechless. <br />The story was well written, thoroughly researched and gave you a small glimpse during that period in the history of my country. Original in its delivery this story will capture the imagination as you read page after page.<br /><br />Thanks for the opportunity Paul.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2506602444688738517" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


