    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_593504057" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/593504057" />
    <a title="Melanie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3046136-melanie"><img alt="Melanie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530731247p2/3046136.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/593504057?book_show_action=true">Apr 17, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melanie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melanie" href="/user/show/3046136-melanie">Melanie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer593504057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15784280137429662759">This is a book about the plight of a child bride in India who is forced into an arranged marriage and then suffers the hardship and harsh judgements that her new widowhood brings after her husband&apos;s untimely death. The story of Usha is a sad one, so be prepared for quite a dramatic story. I have always enjoyed learning of the rich Indian culture and country and this book delivers in its descriptions of the landscapes and culture of both India and Africa, albeit in a tragic and less than glowing </span>
  <span id="freeText15784280137429662759" style="display:none">This is a book about the plight of a child bride in India who is forced into an arranged marriage and then suffers the hardship and harsh judgements that her new widowhood brings after her husband's untimely death. The story of Usha is a sad one, so be prepared for quite a dramatic story. I have always enjoyed learning of the rich Indian culture and country and this book delivers in its descriptions of the landscapes and culture of both India and Africa, albeit in a tragic and less than glowing way. <br /><br />The story was very interesting and kept me engaged throughout. I did have a bit of trouble with the style of writing in that it was more "tell" than "show" in places. The author seemed to want to tell the reader a lot of what the characters were thinking, rather than let their actions show us. I think a little less of that would really warm the reader up to the characters more. I also tripped over the fact that there was too much addressing of the characters by name during conversation. Very rarely do people use the name of the person they are conversing with but it was appearing in almost every line of conversation. However, aside from that, the writing did flow quite nicely and was interesting to read. <br /><br />I liked the twists and turns of the novel and the climax was exciting and satisfying. I loved the ending as well as all the references to the Hindu gods. I felt the book was a great escape to another world and time and definitely provided some food for thought as to how far we've come as a society and how much road we still have to travel. I loved the ending. That is my kind of ending. All in all an enjoyable read, if such a sad and tragic tale can indeed be called "enjoyable." </span>
  <a data-text-id="15784280137429662759" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


