              <span id="reviewTextContainer640320785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6105512446853841293">This book has depth and surprising twists and turns of plot. There was something of the mystery building in it, which was reflected in the language and plot shifts. Essentially it is about the legacy of our history as colonisers and imperialists. It is beautifully crafted, with a strong sense of place. <br/><br/>There is a strong thread running through it, of the question of whether we can influence our fate, or whether we are, in the end, powerless against it. <br/><br/>Striving tends to achieve less than letting </span>
  <span id="freeText6105512446853841293" style="display:none">This book has depth and surprising twists and turns of plot. There was something of the mystery building in it, which was reflected in the language and plot shifts. Essentially it is about the legacy of our history as colonisers and imperialists. It is beautifully crafted, with a strong sense of place. <br /><br />There is a strong thread running through it, of the question of whether we can influence our fate, or whether we are, in the end, powerless against it. <br /><br />Striving tends to achieve less than letting go, in this story, and I found myself reminded of several writers. <br /><br />Haunting, and a book you want to savour and read over a few days.<br /><br />I particularly liked Usha's father, Krishnan, and there was a moment when I was close to tears.</span>
